add(DEV, "06_Menstrual_Cycle_and_Ovulation.txt", "MENSTRUAL CYCLE AND OVULATION", "An illustrated guide to ovarian cycle, uterine cycle, hormones, ovulation, endometrium and cycle variability", "* Menstruation red\n* Follicular phase blue\n* Ovulation gold\n* Luteal phase purple\n* Estrogen green\n* Progesterone orange\n* LH surge pink\n* Endometrium teal", "* Ovary\n* Follicle\n* Mature follicle\n* Ovulation\n* Corpus luteum\n* Uterus\n* Endometrium\n* Cervix\n* FSH\n* LH\n* Estrogen\n* Progesterone", "* Ovarian cycle\n* Uterine cycle\n* Menstruation\n* Follicular phase\n* LH surge\n* Ovulation\n* Luteal phase\n* Endometrial thickening\n* Hormone curves\n* Cycle variability", "* FSH supports follicle development\n* Estrogen rises from growing follicle\n* LH surge triggers ovulation\n* Corpus luteum produces progesterone\n* Endometrium becomes secretory\n* If pregnancy does not occur, hormone levels fall\n* Menstruation begins", "* Irregular cycles\n* Heavy bleeding\n* Severe pain\n* PCOS concept\n* Endometriosis concept\n* Fertility awareness education\n* When to seek medical advice", "Use a circular cycle diagram centrally with hormone curves and ovarian/uterine changes aligned.", "* Do not imply every cycle is exactly 28 days\n* Ovulation timing varies\n* Menstruation is shedding of endometrium, not removal of toxins\n* Avoid fertility guarantees\n* Keep hormone relationships accurate")
add(DEV, "07_Pregnancy_Development_Timeline.txt", "PREGNANCY DEVELOPMENT TIMELINE", "An illustrated guide to embryonic and fetal development, trimesters, organ formation, growth, prenatal care and birth readiness", "* First trimester purple\n* Second trimester blue\n* Third trimester green\n* Placenta pink\n* Fetus gold\n* Organs teal\n* Growth arrows orange\n* Care icons navy", "* Embryo\n* Fetus\n* Placenta\n* Amniotic sac\n* Umbilical cord\n* Neural tube\n* Heart development icon\n* Limb buds\n* Fetal skeleton\n* Uterus\n* Cervix\n* Birth position concept", "* Trimester overview\n* Embryonic period\n* Organogenesis\n* Fetal growth\n* Placenta support\n* Amniotic fluid\n* Prenatal screening\n* Nutrition and folate\n* Fetal movement\n* Birth transition", "* Fertilization and implantation occur\n* Embryonic tissues organize\n* Major organ systems begin forming\n* Fetal period emphasizes growth and maturation\n* Placenta supports exchange\n* Lungs and brain continue maturing\n* Birth transitions breathing and circulation", "* Prenatal care\n* Teratogen avoidance\n* Gestational diabetes screening concept\n* Preeclampsia warning concept\n* Preterm birth\n* Pregnancy warning signs requiring urgent care", "Use a trimester timeline across the centre with proportional, respectful developmental illustrations.", "* Do not show early embryo as a tiny newborn\n* Organogenesis is especially sensitive to teratogens\n* Developmental milestones vary\n* Avoid medical advice beyond prenatal-care guidance\n* Keep language respectful")
add(DEV, "08_Aging_and_Cell_Senescence.txt", "AGING AND CELL SENESCENCE", "An illustrated guide to cellular ageing, telomeres, DNA damage, mitochondria, senescent cells, tissue repair and healthy ageing", "* Telomeres gold\n* DNA damage red\n* Mitochondria orange\n* Senescent cell purple\n* Inflammation pink\n* Stem cells green\n* Repair blue\n* Healthy habits teal", "* Young cell\n* Senescent cell\n* Telomeres\n* Chromosome end\n* DNA damage foci\n* Mitochondria\n* Lysosome\n* Inflammatory signals\n* Stem-cell niche\n* Tissue cross-section", "* Ageing as multi-factorial biology\n* Telomere shortening\n* DNA damage and repair\n* Mitochondrial changes\n* Protein quality control\n* Cellular senescence\n* Stem-cell exhaustion concept\n* Inflammation\n* Tissue resilience\n* Healthy ageing factors", "* Cells divide and experience stress\n* DNA damage accumulates or is repaired\n* Telomeres may shorten in dividing cells\n* Some cells enter senescence\n* Senescent cells release signals\n* Tissue repair capacity changes\n* Lifestyle and medical care influence healthspan", "* Age-related disease risk\n* Frailty concept\n* Neurodegeneration research\n* Cardiovascular ageing\n* Exercise, sleep, nutrition and social connection\n* Anti-ageing hype caution", "Use young-versus-senescent cell comparison centrally, with organism-level ageing panels below.", "* Ageing is not caused by one single mechanism\n* Telomeres are not the entire ageing story\n* Senescence can be protective and harmful depending on context\n* Avoid anti-ageing cure claims\n* Distinguish lifespan and healthspan")
add(DEV, "09_Birth_Defects_and_Teratogens.txt", "BIRTH DEFECTS AND TERATOGENS", "An illustrated guide to congenital anomalies, critical periods, genetic and environmental causes, prevention, screening and respectful care", "* Embryo blue\n* Critical period gold\n* Genes purple\n* Teratogens red\n* Placenta pink\n* Screening teal\n* Prevention green\n* Support orange", "* Embryo timeline\n* Neural tube\n* Heart formation icon\n* Limb development icon\n* Placenta\n* DNA variant icon\n* Medication bottle warning icon\n* Alcohol warning icon\n* Infection icon\n* Ultrasound panel", "* Congenital anomaly definition\n* Genetic causes\n* Chromosomal causes\n* Environmental teratogens\n* Critical periods\n* Dose and timing\n* Folic acid prevention concept\n* Prenatal screening\n* Newborn screening\n* Supportive care and inclusion", "* Development follows timed sequences\n* Genetic and environmental factors can affect patterning\n* Exposure impact depends on timing and dose\n* Screening may identify risk or condition\n* Medical teams plan care\n* Families receive support and counselling", "* Neural tube defects\n* Congenital heart defects\n* Fetal alcohol spectrum disorders\n* Rubella prevention concept\n* Medication safety in pregnancy\n* Genetic counselling\n* Avoiding blame language", "Use critical-period timeline centrally with respectful prevention and care panels.", "* Do not blame parents simplistically\n* Many congenital anomalies have complex or unknown causes\n* Not all anomalies are preventable\n* Screening is not the same as diagnosis\n* Use person-first respectful language")
add(DEV, "10_Lactation_and_Breast_Milk_Biology.txt", "LACTATION AND BREAST MILK BIOLOGY", "An illustrated guide to mammary glands, milk production, hormones, let-down reflex, milk composition and infant nutrition", "* Mammary gland pink\n* Milk ducts blue\n* Alveoli gold\n* Prolactin purple\n* Oxytocin teal\n* Milk droplets white\n* Infant feeding green\n* Immune factors orange", "* Mammary lobule\n* Alveoli\n* Milk-producing cells\n* Myoepithelial cells\n* Milk ducts\n* Nipple\n* Areola\n* Prolactin pathway\n* Oxytocin pathway\n* Milk fat globule\n* Antibodies", "* Mammary gland anatomy\n* Colostrum\n* Mature milk\n* Prolactin and milk production\n* Oxytocin and let-down reflex\n* Supply-demand physiology\n* Milk composition\n* Immune factors\n* Feeding challenges\n* Respectful infant-feeding support", "* Infant suckling stimulates nerves\n* Brain releases prolactin and oxytocin\n* Prolactin supports milk synthesis\n* Oxytocin contracts myoepithelial cells\n* Milk moves through ducts\n* Infant receives nutrients and immune factors\n* Supply responds to milk removal", "* Mastitis\n* Low supply concerns\n* Latch difficulties\n* Formula as medically and practically important option\n* Infant growth monitoring\n* Lactation support", "Use mammary lobule and hormone reflex as central connected diagrams, with milk-composition panel below.", "* Use non-judgmental feeding language\n* Breastfeeding is beneficial but not always possible or chosen\n* Do not shame formula feeding\n* Milk composition changes over time\n* Medical issues need professional support")

add(ANIMAL, "01_Blood_Composition_and_Function.txt", "BLOOD COMPOSITION AND FUNCTION", "An illustrated guide to plasma, red blood cells, white blood cells, platelets, clotting, transport and immunity", "* Plasma yellow\n* Red blood cells red\n* White blood cells blue-purple\n* Platelets gold\n* Clot fibrin teal\n* Oxygen bright red\n* Carbon dioxide grey\n* Antibodies green", "* Plasma\n* Red blood cell\n* Haemoglobin\n* Neutrophil\n* Lymphocyte\n* Monocyte\n* Eosinophil\n* Basophil\n* Platelets\n* Fibrin clot\n* Blood vessel", "* Blood components\n* Oxygen transport\n* Carbon dioxide transport\n* Nutrient and waste transport\n* Immune defence\n* Clotting cascade overview\n* Blood types preview\n* Bone marrow production\n* Complete blood count concept\n* Homeostasis", "* Bone marrow produces blood cells\n* Red cells carry gases\n* Plasma transports solutes\n* White cells defend against infection\n* Platelets adhere to injury\n* Clotting proteins form fibrin\n* Clot stabilizes wound", "* Anaemia\n* Leukaemia concept\n* Infection markers\n* Bleeding disorders\n* Clotting disorders\n* CBC testing\n* Donation safety", "Use a blood vessel cross-section centrally with components enlarged as labelled icons.", "* Red blood cells lack nuclei in mature humans\n* Platelets are cell fragments\n* Clotting is protective but excessive clots can be harmful\n* Do not show all white blood cells as identical\n* Avoid diagnosis from one blood value")
add(ANIMAL, "02_Blood_Groups_and_Transfusion.txt", "BLOOD GROUPS AND TRANSFUSION", "An illustrated guide to ABO and Rh blood groups, antigens, antibodies, compatibility, crossmatching and transfusion safety", "* Type A blue\n* Type B green\n* Type AB purple\n* Type O gold\n* Rh positive red\n* Antibodies teal\n* Agglutination orange\n* Safe transfusion navy", "* Red blood cell\n* A antigen\n* B antigen\n* Rh antigen\n* Anti-A antibody\n* Anti-B antibody\n* Plasma\n* Agglutinated cells\n* Donor bag\n* Recipient vessel\n* Crossmatch test", "* ABO system\n* Rh factor\n* Antigens and antibodies\n* Compatibility principles\n* Universal donor/recipient caveats\n* Crossmatching\n* Transfusion reactions\n* Pregnancy Rh incompatibility concept\n* Blood donation\n* Emergency transfusion safety", "* Donor blood is typed\n* Recipient blood is typed\n* Antibodies are checked\n* Crossmatch tests compatibility\n* Compatible blood is transfused\n* Patient is monitored\n* Incompatible antibodies can cause agglutination and haemolysis", "* Transfusion medicine\n* Surgery and trauma\n* Anaemia treatment\n* Rh immune globulin concept\n* Blood-bank screening\n* Donation eligibility", "Use ABO/Rh compatibility chart centrally with antigen-antibody microinteraction inset.", "* Universal donor/recipient language has caveats and depends on blood component\n* Do not ignore Rh factor\n* Plasma compatibility differs from red-cell compatibility\n* Transfusions require professional testing\n* Avoid implying blood type determines personality or diet needs")
add(ANIMAL, "03_Lymphatic_System_and_Fluid_Balance.txt", "LYMPHATIC SYSTEM AND FLUID BALANCE", "An illustrated guide to lymph vessels, lymph nodes, tissue fluid return, immune surveillance and fat absorption", "* Lymph vessels green\n* Lymph fluid pale yellow\n* Lymph nodes teal\n* Immune cells purple\n* Blood capillaries red-blue\n* Lacteals gold\n* Edema pink\n* Valves blue", "* Lymph capillary\n* Collecting lymph vessel\n* Valve\n* Lymph node\n* Afferent vessel\n* Efferent vessel\n* Thoracic duct\n* Right lymphatic duct\n* Tissue fluid\n* Lacteal\n* Immune cells", "* Lymph formation\n* Fluid return to blood\n* Lymph node filtration\n* Immune surveillance\n* Lacteals and fat absorption\n* Lymph vessel valves\n* Skeletal muscle pump\n* Edema\n* Lymphedema\n* Infection spread through lymph", "* Blood capillaries leak fluid into tissues\n* Most fluid returns to venous blood\n* Excess enters lymph capillaries\n* Lymph moves through vessels and nodes\n* Immune cells inspect lymph\n* Lymph returns to bloodstream\n* Intestinal lacteals carry absorbed fats", "* Swollen lymph nodes\n* Lymphedema\n* Cancer staging concept\n* Infection response\n* Filariasis concept\n* Post-surgical lymph care", "Use full-body lymph map centrally with tissue-fluid exchange and lymph-node cutaway insets.", "* Lymph nodes swell for many reasons, not only cancer\n* Lymphatic system is one-way toward venous blood\n* Distinguish lymph vessels from blood vessels\n* Lacteals absorb fats\n* Avoid diagnosis from node size alone")
add(ANIMAL, "04_Thermoregulation_and_Homeostasis.txt", "THERMOREGULATION AND HOMEOSTASIS", "An illustrated guide to body-temperature control, hypothalamus, sweating, shivering, blood vessels and heat illness", "* Hypothalamus purple\n* Heat red\n* Cooling blue\n* Sweat cyan\n* Skin vessels pink\n* Muscles orange\n* Fever gold\n* Homeostasis green", "* Hypothalamus\n* Skin thermoreceptors\n* Blood vessels\n* Sweat gland\n* Skeletal muscle\n* Brown fat concept\n* Core body thermometer\n* Heat-loss arrows\n* Heat-gain arrows\n* Feedback loop", "* Homeostasis\n* Negative feedback\n* Heat production\n* Heat loss\n* Sweating\n* Vasodilation\n* Vasoconstriction\n* Shivering\n* Fever versus hyperthermia\n* Heat exhaustion and hypothermia overview", "* Temperature receptors detect change\n* Hypothalamus compares to set range\n* If hot, sweating and vasodilation increase heat loss\n* If cold, vasoconstriction and shivering conserve/generate heat\n* Feedback reduces response when temperature normalizes", "* Fever\n* Heat exhaustion\n* Heat stroke warning signs\n* Hypothermia\n* Dehydration\n* Exercise heat stress\n* Infant and elderly risk", "Use a central human silhouette with hot/cold split and feedback loop arrows around hypothalamus.", "* Fever is regulated set-point change; hyperthermia is dangerous overheating\n* Sweating requires evaporation to cool effectively\n* Do not show body temperature as fixed perfectly\n* Heat stroke is an emergency\n* Avoid treatment specifics beyond urgent-care warning")
add(ANIMAL, "05_Osmoregulation_and_Water_Balance.txt", "OSMOREGULATION AND WATER BALANCE", "An illustrated guide to body fluids, kidneys, ADH, thirst, salt balance, dehydration and aquatic animal adaptations", "* Water cyan\n* Sodium yellow\n* ADH purple\n* Kidney red-brown\n* Blood blue-red\n* Thirst centre gold\n* Freshwater fish green\n* Marine fish teal", "* Body fluid compartments\n* Blood plasma\n* Interstitial fluid\n* Cell fluid\n* Hypothalamus\n* Pituitary gland\n* ADH\n* Kidney collecting duct\n* Aquaporins\n* Freshwater fish\n* Marine fish", "* Osmosis\n* Osmolarity\n* ADH regulation\n* Thirst response\n* Kidney concentration of urine\n* Sodium balance\n* Dehydration\n* Overhydration\n* Freshwater versus marine fish osmoregulation\n* Desert animal adaptations", "* Blood osmolarity rises\n* Hypothalamus detects change\n* Thirst increases\n* Pituitary releases ADH\n* Kidneys insert aquaporins in collecting ducts\n* More water is reabsorbed\n* Urine becomes concentrated\n* Osmolarity returns toward normal", "* Dehydration\n* Hyponatremia concept\n* Diabetes insipidus concept\n* Kidney disease\n* Heat illness\n* Animal adaptation examples", "Use human ADH-kidney pathway centrally, with freshwater/marine animal comparison panel below.", "* Osmosis is water movement across membranes\n* ADH affects water reabsorption, not direct salt pumping as main action\n* Drinking too much water can be dangerous in some contexts\n* Fish osmoregulation differs by habitat\n* Avoid personal hydration prescriptions")
add(ANIMAL, "06_Excretion_and_Nitrogenous_Waste.txt", "EXCRETION AND NITROGENOUS WASTE", "An illustrated guide to ammonia, urea, uric acid, kidneys, liver, nephrons and animal excretory adaptations", "* Ammonia red\n* Urea blue\n* Uric acid white\n* Liver brown\n* Kidney purple\n* Nephron teal\n* Aquatic animals cyan\n* Birds/reptiles gold", "* Amino acid\n* Ammonia\n* Liver\n* Urea cycle icon\n* Kidney nephron\n* Urine\n* Fish gill\n* Bird uric acid paste\n* Mammal\n* Insect Malpighian tubules", "* Protein breakdown\n* Nitrogenous waste toxicity\n* Ammonia excretion\n* Urea production\n* Uric acid excretion\n* Water conservation tradeoffs\n* Mammalian kidney role\n* Fish gills\n* Insect excretion\n* Evolutionary adaptation", "* Proteins are broken down\n* Amino groups produce ammonia\n* Aquatic animals may excrete ammonia directly\n* Mammal liver converts ammonia to urea\n* Kidneys remove urea in urine\n* Birds, reptiles and insects often conserve water using uric acid", "* Kidney failure concept\n* Liver failure ammonia buildup concept\n* Gout as uric acid crystal disease\n* Animal habitat adaptations\n* Water conservation", "Use a nitrogenous-waste comparison chart centrally with animal examples and liver-kidney pathway.", "* Ammonia, urea and uric acid have different toxicity and water-cost tradeoffs\n* Humans mainly excrete urea, not uric acid as main nitrogen waste\n* Liver converts ammonia to urea\n* Do not show kidneys producing all urea\n* Avoid oversimplifying all animal groups")
add(ANIMAL, "07_Animal_Reproduction_Strategies.txt", "ANIMAL REPRODUCTION STRATEGIES", "An illustrated guide to sexual and asexual reproduction, internal and external fertilization, eggs, live birth and parental care", "* Asexual reproduction teal\n* Sexual reproduction purple\n* Eggs gold\n* Sperm blue\n* Internal fertilization red\n* External fertilization cyan\n* Parental care green\n* Larvae orange", "* Budding hydra\n* Fragmentation concept\n* Egg\n* Sperm\n* External fertilization in water\n* Internal fertilization\n* Amniotic egg\n* Placenta concept\n* Larval stage\n* Parent-offspring care", "* Asexual reproduction\n* Sexual reproduction\n* Gametes\n* Internal versus external fertilization\n* Oviparity\n* Viviparity\n* Ovoviviparity\n* Larval development\n* Metamorphosis\n* Parental investment tradeoffs", "* Adults produce gametes or clones\n* Fertilization occurs internally or externally\n* Embryos develop in eggs, uterus or protected structures\n* Offspring hatch or are born\n* Growth may include larval stages\n* Survival is influenced by parental care and environment", "* Aquaculture\n* Conservation breeding\n* Invasive species reproduction\n* Pollination analogy caution\n* Reproductive health in animals\n* Life-history strategies", "Use a comparative grid of animal reproduction modes with life-cycle arrows.", "* Do not imply one strategy is superior\n* External fertilization usually requires moist/aquatic environment\n* Asexual reproduction can produce rapid clones but reduces genetic variation\n* Parental care varies widely\n* Avoid anthropomorphic framing")
add(ANIMAL, "08_Circadian_Rhythms_and_Sleep.txt", "CIRCADIAN RHYTHMS AND SLEEP", "An illustrated guide to biological clocks, light cues, melatonin, sleep stages, body rhythms and health", "* Biological clock purple\n* Light yellow\n* Melatonin blue\n* Sleep stages navy\n* REM teal\n* Body temperature red\n* Cortisol orange\n* Jet lag grey", "* Suprachiasmatic nucleus\n* Retina light input\n* Pineal gland\n* Melatonin\n* Sleep-wake cycle\n* NREM stages\n* REM sleep\n* Body temperature rhythm\n* Cortisol rhythm\n* Clock genes", "* Circadian rhythm\n* Zeitgebers\n* Light-dark cycle\n* Melatonin timing\n* Sleep architecture\n* REM and NREM sleep\n* Memory and repair concepts\n* Shift work\n* Jet lag\n* Sleep hygiene education", "* Light reaches retina\n* Signals reach suprachiasmatic nucleus\n* Clock synchronizes body rhythms\n* Pineal melatonin changes with darkness\n* Sleep stages cycle through night\n* Morning light resets timing\n* Disruption shifts rhythms", "* Insomnia concept\n* Sleep deprivation\n* Shift-work disorder concept\n* Jet lag\n* Mental health links\n* Metabolic health links\n* When to seek medical help for sleep problems", "Use a 24-hour clock body-rhythm diagram centrally with sleep-stage hypnogram below.", "* Melatonin is a timing signal, not a knockout sedative\n* Sleep is active brain physiology\n* REM is not the only important sleep stage\n* Circadian rhythms are not just habits\n* Avoid supplement dosing advice")
add(ANIMAL, "09_Exercise_Physiology_and_Muscle_Energy.txt", "EXERCISE PHYSIOLOGY AND MUSCLE ENERGY", "An illustrated guide to ATP systems, oxygen delivery, muscle fibres, cardiovascular response, training adaptation and fatigue", "* ATP gold\n* Phosphocreatine purple\n* Glycolysis orange\n* Aerobic metabolism blue\n* Muscle fibres red\n* Oxygen cyan\n* Heart crimson\n* Adaptation green", "* Skeletal muscle\n* Muscle fibre types\n* Mitochondria\n* Capillary\n* Myoglobin\n* ATP\n* Phosphocreatine\n* Glucose\n* Lactate\n* Heart\n* Lung\n* Sweat gland", "* Immediate ATP-PC system\n* Anaerobic glycolysis\n* Aerobic metabolism\n* Oxygen delivery\n* Heart rate and stroke volume\n* Ventilation\n* Muscle fibre types\n* Lactate concept\n* Fatigue mechanisms\n* Training adaptations", "* Exercise begins\n* Stored ATP is used quickly\n* Phosphocreatine regenerates ATP briefly\n* Glycolysis increases ATP production\n* Aerobic metabolism rises with oxygen delivery\n* Heart and lungs increase supply\n* Training improves capacity over time", "* Endurance training\n* Strength training\n* Overtraining concept\n* Heat illness\n* Rhabdomyolysis warning concept\n* Sports nutrition basics\n* Medical clearance for risk groups", "Use a working muscle connected to heart and lungs centrally, with three energy systems as timeline panels.", "* Lactate is not simply a waste poison\n* Energy systems overlap, not switch on/off sharply\n* Training adaptations are specific to activity\n* Avoid exercise prescriptions\n* Fatigue has multiple causes")
add(ANIMAL, "10_Comparative_Animal_Circulation_and_Respiration.txt", "COMPARATIVE ANIMAL CIRCULATION AND RESPIRATION", "An illustrated guide to gills, lungs, tracheae, open and closed circulation, heart chambers and animal adaptation", "* Gills blue\n* Lungs pink\n* Tracheae teal\n* Open circulation orange\n* Closed circulation red\n* Hearts purple\n* Oxygen gold\n* Water cyan", "* Fish gills\n* Insect tracheal tubes\n* Amphibian skin/lungs\n* Bird air sacs\n* Mammal alveoli\n* Open circulatory system\n* Closed vessels\n* Two-chamber heart\n* Three-chamber heart\n* Four-chamber heart", "* Gas exchange surfaces\n* Countercurrent exchange\n* Tracheal systems\n* Book lungs concept\n* Open circulation\n* Closed circulation\n* Fish, amphibian, reptile, bird and mammal heart patterns\n* Single versus double circulation\n* Metabolic demand\n* Habitat adaptation", "* Oxygen diffuses across specialized surface\n* Circulation or tracheal tubes distribute gases\n* Water or air flows over exchange surface\n* Blood or hemolymph transports materials\n* Heart structure supports circulation pattern\n* Adaptations match body size, activity and habitat", "* Aquatic hypoxia\n* Diving mammals\n* Bird flight physiology\n* Insect size limits concept\n* Evolution of vertebrate circulation\n* Environmental change impacts", "Use a comparative animal panel grid with gas-exchange and circulation diagrams side by side.", "* Open circulation is not absent circulation\n* Insects mainly deliver oxygen through tracheae, not blood like mammals\n* Fish gills use countercurrent exchange\n* Bird lungs use air sacs and one-way airflow\n* Avoid ranking systems as simply better")

add(BIOTECH, "01_PCR_Polymerase_Chain_Reaction.txt", "PCR: POLYMERASE CHAIN REACTION", "An illustrated guide to DNA amplification, primers, thermal cycling, polymerase, gel verification and diagnostic use", "* Template DNA blue\n* Primers green\n* Polymerase purple\n* Nucleotides gold\n* Heat denaturation red\n* Annealing cyan\n* Extension orange\n* Amplicons teal", "* DNA template\n* Forward primer\n* Reverse primer\n* DNA polymerase\n* dNTPs\n* Thermal cycler\n* Denaturation stage\n* Annealing stage\n* Extension stage\n* Amplified DNA band", "* PCR components\n* Primer design concept\n* Thermal cycling\n* Denaturation\n* Annealing\n* Extension\n* Exponential amplification\n* Controls\n* Gel or fluorescence detection\n* Applications in diagnosis, forensics and research", "* DNA is heated to separate strands\n* Temperature lowers for primers to bind\n* Polymerase extends new strands\n* Cycle repeats\n* Target region doubles repeatedly\n* Product is detected by gel or fluorescence\n* Controls validate interpretation", "* Infectious disease testing\n* Genetic testing\n* Forensics\n* Environmental DNA\n* Contamination risk\n* False positives and false negatives\n* Laboratory quality control", "Use thermal cycling as a central loop with DNA copy number increasing visually.", "* PCR amplifies a target sequence, not whole organisms\n* Primer specificity matters\n* Contamination can cause false positives\n* A negative result depends on sample quality and assay limits\n* Do not show polymerase working during denaturation")
